flowRoot.flowPara: Black hole-black hole (BH-BH) binaries are sources gravitational waves (GWs) during inspiral and merger events. With the advent of Advanced Virgo/LIGO it is important to estimate the demography of such promising sources of GWs. We have run N-body simulations of young dense star clusters, with stellar and binary evolution, to investigate the impact of dynamics and metallicity on the formation and evolution of BH-BH binaries (Ziosi et al. 2014). The simulated clusters are dense enough to provide a perfect environment to probe the effect of dynamics on short timescales, while their size makes them suitable for being simulated with direct N-body codes.
Ziosi et al., 2014, MNRAS, 441, 3703
Mapelli et al. 2013, MNRAS, 429, 2298

Coalescence timescale (tGW) is the time a system needs to reach semi-major axis a=0 due to orbital decay by GW emission (Peters 1964)
Only two simulated BH-BH have tGW< tH (where tH is the Hubble time), and thus could be important for GW emission
